Waves and Light

Explore waves through sound, light, and more!

Chapter: Wave Behaviors
Quiz: Interference

Science and Engineering

Mallard Musical Chairs

In the popular game "musical waves", played by ducklings the world over, when the music stops, players need to be bobbing in a spot that rises and falls as much as possible.

On each round, the duckling reaching the smallest maximum height is eliminated, so, in the game above, the duckling with the green cap is out.

The game is best played with one or more artificial wave generators or, to make things tricky, around jagged coastlines. Can you predict who will win?

If you’ve ever been to a water park with a “wave pool,” you may have noticed that the waves are generated at a single point in the pool, but there are other places where the waves seem bigger. This is caused by two classic wave behaviors: reflection and interference

Reflection is a familiar enough idea — when waves hit a wall, they bounce off it, like light hitting a mirror or sound echoing. Interference is a little bit trickier. The idea is that when two waves cross paths, they appear “added together” at any particular point. So when one wave peak passes through another peak, you get a “super-peak” that is as high as the two original peaks added together.

  • Source waves
  • Observed wave

When the peak of one wave meets the trough of another, they appear to "add" to zero, canceling each other out. For an instant, the water's surface is flat. You can see both kinds of interference in the animated plot above.

You can observe interference with all kinds of of waves. In fact, this is how noise-canceling headphones work and experiments with interference provided key evidence that light and matter particles are wave-like.

In a wave pool, the waves reflect off the walls of the pool and then interfere, creating certain spots where you see big waves because peaks always meet other peaks. You can also see other spots where peaks cancel with troughs and not much happens.

  • reflected wave
  • observed wave

In the animation above, the blue wave is the original wave from a source. The green wave is the same wave reflected off a wall. You wouldn't actually observe either of these though — you would see the red wave, which is the combined effect of the blue and green. Notice that the biggest peaks of the red wave are always in the same places, although the source wave and the reflected wave travel right- and left-ward.

The pattern gets more interesting when there are two sources on an open expanse of water. In the plot on the left below, two wave generators are moving up and down in time with each other. You can move a duck around to observe the resulting wave using the sliders.

The duck starts out at an equal distance from each wave generator where the peaks produced by each source will hit at the same time. This means that the duck experiences a bigger wave, which you can see on the right plot.

But if you shift the yyy-position of the duck up to y=0.4,y = 0.4,y=0.4, the resulting wave has almost completely disappeared and the water hardly moves. You can find many calm places like this if you keep looking.

How can these calm places occur right next to huge waves? If you toggle the “Show source waves” button, you can see that the waves from each source are out of sync with each other at the calm points. If you find another place where the waves are high, you should see the source waves come back into sync.

This observation can help us predict whether a duck's position is calm or wavy. The key is the difference in the duck's distance to each source. If the difference is a whole number (1,2,3,… )(1,2,3,\dots)(1,2,3,…) of wavelengths, then the peaks of the waves arrive together and they add to make a "super-peak."

If the waves generated by the sources have wavelength 1 m,\SI{1}{\meter},1 m, this duck is sitting on a "super-peak." If the waves generated have wavelength 2 m,\SI{2}{\meter},2 m, then this duck will likely be eliminated from the game.

However, if the distance from the duck to the sources is different by a half wavelength, the peak from one source lines up with the trough of the other, and the water at the duck's position will be calm. This also happens when the difference is 1.51.51.5 or 2.52.52.5 wavelengths (or any "whole number plus a half" wavelengths).

Comparing the wavelength and the path length difference is usually all you need to make predictions about which duck will win the game.

Today's Challenge

In round one of Musical Waves, two ducks sit on the line between two red wave generators. The generators move up and down together and both produce identical waves of wavelength 2 m.\SI{2}{\meter}.2 m.

The duck with the smallest maximum height as it bobs over the waves will be eliminated. Which duck will win the round?

Note: The generators are not wide enough to produce any appreciable reflected wave.

Daffy Donald It's a tie.

Correct!

    João Pedro Afonso
    Apr 26, 2020

    Daffy is 1 wavelength (1λ1\lambda1λ) from the left generator and 2 from the right. That means it is picking the intensity of the waves generated 1 period (1T1T1T) before at the left generator, and the intensity generated 2 periods before at the right. Since the generators are bobbing together, that means the intensity is always in the same direction when they meet at Daffy point: both high, both low, both at level... it's a constructive interference at its maximum.

    Donald however, is 1.25 wavelength from the left generator, and 1.75 from the right. The intensity for the left wave was generated 1.25T1.25T1.25T before, the right, 1.75T1.75T1.75T. There's always an half period of difference, which means that when the left generator is high, the right is low, and vice-versa. The interference is destructive. Donald looses.

    explanation

    A wave is a phenomena that repeats itself in space and time. Its intensity in one point, is the intensity that occurred in other point of the wave (from the direction it comes), some time ago. One wavelength is the minimum distance for which there is repetition, one period is the minimum time. It comes from that, that the wave's intensity we experiment at certain point, is the same intensity that occurred one wavelength afar, one period in the past. In particular, if we know how much afar from an wave generator is certain point, we know when the wave that passes through it was generated. In the graph below, you'll see representations of the waves generated and how they can be propagated in space and time:

    Water waves are tricky. Surely you must have already learn that the water from an wave is not flowing in the direction of the wave, but instead it move in circles in the same point. If we substitute a volume of water by a duck, it will move in circles too... going up and down for that reason too. I'm unable to easily explain how it comes to be like that, but if you have patience, you can do the experience using real waves. If a material point of the wave moves in circles (including the ducks), we can represent them by clock hour pointers moving clockwise. A quarter period before, the clock will mark 3 hours less, half period, 6h, and so on. A quarter of wavelength afar (in the direction of the wave), the clock will mark 3 hours less, a quarter period before, 6 hours less, and so on. When we have two waves, we need to sum the interference of both in the points... in our case, to do a vector sum of clock pointers in the points of interest. Daffy sees its clocks always in the same direction, so, the effect is always added. But Donald sees them always opposed. So, it don't moves.

    Now, for a warning and a challenge:

    • The warning: I draw the waves along space always with the same intensity. This is only correct if the wave conserves its energy , but also if they are planar. If they are circular waves, then the wave front will grow up and the intensity will decrease with distance from the generator while its energy will be distributed by a bigger and bigger front-wave. I assumed in my solution that the ducks are in a straight channel, one of those where we can create sollitons (which are a quite nice thing to do... try to do one in one of those feet washers surrounding some leisure swimming pools ), and where we can trust the waves to not loose intensity.

    • The challenge: There's a potential fatal flaw in my representation. It will not affect the practical result of answering the puzzle, but it might affect some other predictions we might think for it... the challenge is to point what it is (in other words, I consciously draw an erroneous graph... to avoid explain other things).

    Yes, you could use the cosine instead of the sine. The starting phase or moment is not specified.

    In general, a wave obeys the equation y(x,t)=Asin⁡2π(t−t0τ−xλ),y(x,t) = A\sin 2\pi\left(\frac {t - t_0} \tau - \frac x \lambda\right),y(x,t)=Asin2π(τt−t0​​−λx​), with t0t_0t0​ the starting time, τ\tauτ the period, λ\lambdaλ the wavelength, AAA the amplitude;

    The idea is that at x=0x = 0x=0, the wave has harmonic motion, going from phase sin⁡0\sin 0sin0 to sin⁡2π\sin 2\pisin2π in one period; thus y(0,t)=Asin⁡2πtτ.y(0,t) = A\sin \frac{2\pi t}\tau.y(0,t)=Asinτ2πt​. The wave arrives at position xxx with a delay, so that y(x,t)=y(0,t−x/v)=Asin⁡2π(t−x/vτ)=Asin⁡2π(tτ−xvτ)=Asin⁡2π(tτ−xλ).\begin{aligned}y(x,t) & = y(0,t - x/v) = A\sin 2\pi\left(\frac{t - x/v}\tau\right) \\ & = A\sin 2\pi\left(\frac t \tau - \frac x {v\tau}\right) \\ & = A\sin 2\pi\left(\frac t \tau - \frac x \lambda\right).\end{aligned}y(x,t)​=y(0,t−x/v)=Asin2π(τt−x/v​)=Asin2π(τt​−vτx​)=Asin2π(τt​−λx​).​

    Or also, y(x,t)=Asin⁡(ωt−k⋅x+ϕ0),y(\mathbf x,t) = A\sin (\omega t - \mathbf k\cdot \mathbf x + \phi_0),y(x,t)=Asin(ωt−k⋅x+ϕ0​), where ω=2πf=2π/τ\omega = 2\pi f = 2\pi/\tauω=2πf=2π/τ is the angular frequency, k=2π/λk = 2\pi/\lambdak=2π/λ is the wave number and ϕ0\phi_0ϕ0​ the initial phase at the origin; and k\mathbf kk can be taken as a vector to account for waves in different directions.

    With complex numbers, one can also use the notation y(x,t)=Aei(ωt−k⋅x),y(\mathbf x, t) = Ae^{i(\omega t - \mathbf k\cdot \mathbf x)},y(x,t)=Aei(ωt−k⋅x), where the modulus ∣A∣|A|∣A∣ is the amplitude and the argument arg A\text{arg}\ Aarg A is the initial phase.

    The wavelength is 2m so as long as the path difference (from generator 1 to duck and generator 2 to duck) is an integer multiple of 2m, there will be constructive interference and the largest possible peaks and troughs.

    Daffy - path difference is 4m - 2m = 2m so this will be winner.

    Donald - path difference is 3.5 - 2.5 = 1m

    1m is half a wavelength; so a peak of one will arrive at the same time as a trough of the other wave & will cancel out (the waves will always arrive half a wavelength out of synch so always net displacement = 0 (cancel each other out)

    Mallard Musical Chairs says that if the difference between the duck's distance to each source is a whole number (1,2,3,4,…) of wavelengths, then the peaks of the waves arrive together and they add to make a "super-peak."

    However, if the distance from the duck to the sources is different by a half wavelength, the peak from one source lines up with the trough of the other, and the water at the duck's position will be calm.

    The generators produce identical waves of wavelength 2m ⇒ 1m, 2m, 3m, 4m,… are all points of maximum height.

    • Daffy is 2m away from the left generator and 4m from the right generator, Daffy is on the point of maximum height.

    • Donald is 3.5m from the left generator and 2.5m from the right generator, which is half-way between two maxima and therefore has a maximum height of 0m.

    So Daffy wins the round.

    Alec Benzer
    Apr 26, 2020

    You're only considering the left wave. But the left wave will be combined with the right wave. You need to look at a duck's distance from both waves and look at the difference. Is the difference is an integer number of wavelengths, the waves are in sync, and you'll get a super peak. If the difference is off by a half wavelength (.5, 1.5, 2.5, ...), the waves will cancel each other out and you won't move at all.

    If only the left wave existed, then actually there would be no difference between the heights achieved by either duck. The wave "moves" over time, so Daffy and Donald would both reach the same max height (though not at the same time).

    You need to calculate the difference in the duck's distance to each source, in terms of number of wave lengths. I think you can do that because both wavelengths are 2m.

    Daffy is 4m (2 wavelengths) from one generator and 2m (1 wavelength) from the other generator; 2 wavelengths - 1 wavelength = 1 wavelength. This is a whole number, so Daffy will be on a super-peak.

    Donald is 3.5m (1.75 wavelengths) from one generator and 2.5m (1.25 wavelengths) from the other generator; 1.75 wavelengths - 1.25 wavelengths = 0.5 wavelength. This is a not a whole number, so Daffy will not be on a super-peak.

    Daffy will be on the higher peak, so Daffy wins the round.

    (I'm too much of a beginner here to start using sin and cos curves!)

    Waves with a displacement of 2m will reach the maximum amplitude at 1m intervals starting from 0m and minimum amplitude at 1m intervals starting from 0.5m.

    Daffy stands at 2m which is a point of maximum amplitude which is at 1m intervals.

    Whereas Donald stands at 2m + 1.5m which is 3.5m which is at a point of minimum amplitude at 0.5m intervals.

    So, Daffy wins

    In musical waves, the goal is to achieve the highest height. Each wavelength is 2m2m2m, meaning that Daffy will be at the crest of a wave at their highest, while Donald will not be at the crest of a wave; he will reside on the rest position (bottom of the amplitude when measured from the crest). Daffy's motion will be similar to the RedRedRed DuckDuckDuck in the example, while Donald's motion will be similar to the GreenGreenGreen DuckDuckDuck.
